---
// ATS Explained — plain-English definition section

import Section from '../../ui/Section.astro'
import Row from '../../ui/Row.astro'
import Col from '../../ui/Col.astro'
---

<Section id="ats-explained">
	<Row>
		<Col span="2" />
		<Col span="8" align="center">
			<h2 class="text-pretty">ATS, <strong>explained in plain English.</strong></h2>
			<p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400">
				An <strong>Applicant Tracking System (ATS)</strong> is software employers use to collect, sort,
				and filter the CVs they receive. When you apply for a job online, your CV usually goes into an
				ATS first, not onto a recruiter's desk.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-4 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400">
				The ATS scans your CV, pulls out your details, and ranks or filters candidates based on how
				well they match the job. Only the CVs that clear that first pass are seen by a human.
			</p>
		</Col>
		<Col span="2" />
	</Row>
	<Row>
		<Col span="12">
			<div
				class="mx-auto mt-10 max-w-3xl rounded-2xl bg-primary-50 px-8 py-6 text-center dark:bg-primary-950/30"
			>
				<p class="text-xl font-semibold text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-300">
					In short: <strong>the ATS decides whether a person ever reads your CV at all.</strong>
				</p>
			</div>
		</Col>
	</Row>
</Section>
